  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering at both federal and state levels:\n\n1. Federal Statutes:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n- Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020\n\n2. Key Federal Provisions:\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 (money laundering criminal statute)\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1957 (monetary transactions in criminal proceeds)\n\n3. State Statutes:\n- Most states have their own money laundering laws\n- These often mirror federal statutes\n- Provide additional prosecution mechanisms\n\n4. International Cooperation:\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Various international treaties and agreements\n\nThese statutes generally:\n- Criminalize money laundering activities\n- Require financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Establish reporting and record-keeping requirements\n- Provide for civil and criminal penalties\n- Enable asset forfeiture\n\nPenalties can include significant fines and imprisonment, depending on the specific circumstances and severity of the offense.",
